features.description:
Starting at 20th level, you learn that mastering any particular path or style would ruin your freeform form of combat. You've become the pinnacle of adaptability and battlefield flexibility gaining the following benefits;
• You regain 1 spent Superiority Die at the beginning of each of your turns.
• All jutsu you cast of C-Rank and lower are treated as your Signature Jutsu.

With a flicker of chakra and a glance sharpened by experience, you uncover the faults in their technique. You aren't just exploiting their weakness. You are their weakness. Starting at 6th level, in place of an attack made as part of your attack action or as a Bonus Action, you may make a Maintain Focus check vs a creature you can see within 60 feet Constitution Save DC. On a success, you identify the following;
Natural Perception. You become aware of the nature releases the target has access to.
Weakness Tracing. You perceive a flaw in their defense that only their nature release techniques can exploit. The target creature gains the Momentary Flaw condition until the end of your next turn.

Starting at 6th level, your technique and grace expands you mobility across the battlefield. When you cast a Bukijutsu that forces a hostile creature to make a saving throw, you can spend 3 Discipline. When you do, depending on your current dance, you gain its associated effects;
• If you are in Waltz, your Partner can make a weapon attack against the same target before their saving throw is made. On a successful hit, the hostile creature makes their saving throw at disadvantage.
• If you are in Samba you can cast a second Bukijutsu of the same rank or lower, that also forces a saving throw, but with a different ability score (Ex. If your jutsu forces a Dexterity save, the second jutsu cannot also force a Dexterity save.). This second Bukijutsu will only affect the original target, even if would normally affect an area. The original target makes a saving throw against both, simultaneously. If they fail either saving throw, they suffer the effects of both Bukijutsu as if they failed both. If they succeed against both, they only suffer the success effects of the originally triggered Bukijutsu.
